Worker-scoped fixtures (e.g., `{ scope: 'worker' }`) are created once and shared across all tests in a worker, ideal for expensive setups like organizations or projects. Test-scoped fixtures (default) are created fresh for each test, suitable for mutable data. Example:
typescript
// Worker-scoped fixture (shared across all tests in a worker)
const sharedOrg = baseFixtures.extend<{ org: Org }>({
  org: async ({}, use) => {
    const org = await api.createOrg();
    await use(org);
  }
});

// Test-scoped fixture (fresh per test)
const project = baseFixtures.extend<{ project: Project }>({
  project: async ({ org }, use) => {
    const project = await api.createProject(org.id);
    await use(project);
  }
});

The project structure was split into 7 projects by MFE folder (Applications, Organizations, Projects, etc.), each with `dependencies: ['Setup']`. This allowed targeted test execution, grouped HTML reports, and parallelism control. Example:
typescript
module.exports = defineConfig({
  projects: [
    { name: 'Applications',  testDir: 'apps/ui/applications/e2e', dependencies: ['Setup'] },
    { name: 'Organizations', testDir: 'apps/ui/organizations/e2e', dependencies: ['Setup'] },
    { name: 'Projects',      testDir: 'apps/ui/projects/e2e',      dependencies: ['Setup'] },
    // ... other projects
  ]
});
